2. Writing your success story

a) Cleaning the Text and Word Cloud

library(tm)

removeNumPunct <- function(x){
  gsub("[^[:alpha:][:space:]]*", "", x)
}

clean_corpus <- function(corpus){
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removePunctuation)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeWords, c(stopwords("en")))  
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeNumbers)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(removeNumPunct))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, stripWhitespace)
  return(corpus)
}

stemcompletion2 <- function(x, dictionary) {
   x <- unlist(strsplit(as.character(x), " "))
   x <- x[x != ""]
   x <- stemCompletion(x, dictionary=dictionary)
   x <- paste(x, sep="", collapse=" ")
   PlainTextDocument(stripWhitespace(x))
}
#subsetting most successful and least successful projects
kickstarter <- kickstarter %>% arrange(desc(pledged))

#Create function to get word frequency
get_word_frequency <- function(blah){
  # build a corpus, and specify the source to be character vectors
  blurb_corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(blah))
  #apply the text cleaning function to the original corpus
  corpus_clean <- clean_corpus(blurb_corpus)
  #keep a copy of corpus to use later as a dictionary for stem completion
  corpus_clean_copy <- corpus_clean
  #stemming
  corpus_stem <- tm_map(corpus_clean, stemDocument)
  #stem completion
  corpus_comp <- lapply(corpus_stem, stemcompletion2, dictionary = corpus_clean_copy)
  #convert list into a corpus
  corpus_comp <- as.VCorpus(corpus_comp)
 
  tdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(corpus_comp)
  tdm_m <- as.matrix(tdm)
  word.freq <- sort(rowSums(tdm_m), decreasing = T)

  return(word.freq)
}

The boxplot above shows that the more reabable and easier the project description is, it is more likely for a project to be suspended, as suspended projects seem to have the lowest median and minimum Fresch-Kincaid Reading Ease Score. However, although successful projects have slightly higher median Fresch-Kincaid Reading Ease Score, the median was not significantly different from that of other “unsuccessful” projects, such as projects that failed or got canceled. In this sense, this boxplot shows that readability is not the strongest indicator of a project’s likelihood of success.

# function to create the sentiment score 
sentiment <- function(words=c("really great good stuff bad")){
  require(quanteda)
  tok <- quanteda::tokens(words)
  pos.count <- sum(tok[[1]]%in%pos[,1])
  neg.count <- sum(tok[[1]]%in%neg[,1])
  out <- (pos.count - neg.count)/(pos.count+neg.count)
  out
}

#create heatmap 
ks_grouped=(kickstarter_with_sents %>% group_by(state,senti)

   geom_tile()+
    geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(freq, 4))) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low="white", high="pink")

An interesting observation can be found from the heatmap above: More failed projects showed higher sentiment score than successful ones, meaning that being overly optimistic in describing your project may not be the best method in optimizing the chances of success. In fact, more successful projects had the sentiment score of -1 than failed projects.

#apply function to get term-document-matrix
get_tdm<- function(blah){
  # build a corpus, and specify the source to be character vectors
  blurb_corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(blah))
  #apply the text cleaning function to the original corpus
  corpus_clean <- clean_corpus(blurb_corpus)
  #keep a copy of corpus to use later as a dictionary for stem completion
  corpus_clean_copy <- corpus_clean
  #stemming
  corpus_stem <- tm_map(corpus_clean, stemDocument)
  #stem completion
  corpus_comp <- lapply(corpus_stem, stemcompletion2, dictionary = corpus_clean_copy)
  #convert list into a corpus
  corpus_comp <- as.VCorpus(corpus_comp)
 
  tdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(corpus_comp)
  return(tdm)
}
